{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08992609-55d6-4181-adb4-159eda64eb89","content":"Here's what you'll encounter upgrading to .NET 10:\n\n**1. SslStream algorithm properties** — **Compile warnings** (obsolete). `KeyExchangeAlgorithm`, `CipherAlgorithm`, `HashAlgorithm`, and their `*Strength` counterparts are marked `[Obsolete]`. They return meaningless values for TLS 1.3 connections. Use `SslStream.NegotiatedCipherSuite` instead.\n\n**2. SystemEvents.EventsThreadShutdown** — **Compile warning** (obsolete). This event is obsoleted in .NET 10. Remove the callback or suppress the warning if the cleanup logic is handled elsewhere.\n\n**3. Queryable.MaxBy with IComparer\\<TSource>** — **Compile error** (CS0121 ambiguous call). .NET 10 adds this overload natively to `Queryable`. If you had a custom extension method providing it, the compiler can't resolve which one to call. Remove your custom extension method and use the built-in one.\n\n**4. XsltSettings.EnableScript = true** — **Runtime error**. .NET 10 removes support for embedded `<msxsl:script>` blocks in XSLT for security reasons. Code compiles fine but throws at execution time when loading a stylesheet containing script blocks. Refactor scripting logic out of XSLT into C# code or use `XsltArgumentList` extension objects as an alternative.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8aa108db-684a-4157-994d-aac1b3eabfb2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about breaking changes and warnings when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each of the four areas they mentioned:\n\n1. **SslStream.KeyExchangeAlgorithm, SslStream.CipherAlgorithm, SslStream.HashAlgorithm and their strength properties** - In .NET 10, these properties on SslStream have been obsoleted. They were already returning meaningless values for TLS 1.3 connections since TLS 1.3 doesn't expose individual algorithm details the same way. The properties are marked with `[Obsolete]` attributes, which means they'll generate